          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can prepaid expenses be amortised?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, and that is exactly how they are treated. The payment is first recorded as a prepaid asset, then charged to profit and loss over the period it covers. Insurance of Rs 60,000 paid on 1 April for twelve months is amortised at Rs 5,000 a month, leaving Rs 15,000 sitting as a prepaid asset on 31 December."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between prepaid expenses and amortization?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A prepaid expense is the asset created when payment runs ahead of consumption, while amortisation is the process of writing that asset off to profit and loss over time. Amortisation also applies to intangible assets such as software licences. The prepaid balance is a balance sheet figure; the amortisation charge belongs to the profit and loss account."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is a prepaid expense allowed as a deduction in the year of payment under the Income Tax Act?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Usually no. Under the mercantile system recognised in Section 145, expenditure is allowed in the year to which it relates, so the unexpired portion is disallowed and claimed the following year. The exception is Section 43B items such as statutory dues, employer contributions and specified interest, which are allowed only in the year actually paid."
          }
        }
